```

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:11Z on core/notifications/getNotifications.ts:46 ---
`unreadOnly` is implemented by fetching rows without a `read=false` filter and then filtering in memory. This makes pagination inconsistent (you can return < `limit` rows) and `total` becomes just the page size, not the true total. Apply the unread filter in the DB query and compute `total` via a `count(*)` query (or return a separate `pageTotal` if that’s the intention).

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:11Z on core/notifications/getNotifications.ts:63 ---
`deleteNotification` ignores the `userId` parameter in the delete `where` clause, so a caller who can guess an ID could delete another user's notification. Include `notifications.userId = userId` in the delete predicate (and ideally return false when no row matched both).

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:11Z on app/api/auth/google/route.ts:21 ---
OAuth `state` is generated but never persisted (cookie/session) so it cannot be validated on callback, leaving the flow open to CSRF/login injection. Store the `state` server-side (e.g., as a CSRF cookie using `CSRF_COOKIE_NAME` + `getCsrfCookieOptions`) and validate it in the callback before exchanging the code.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:11Z on app/api/auth/google/callback/route.ts:22 ---
This route uses `redirect()` from `next/navigation` inside a Route Handler wrapped by `withErrorHandler`. `redirect()` throws, so it will likely be caught and turned into a JSON error response instead of a 302. Also, the OAuth callback does not validate the `state` parameter against a stored value/cookie. Use `Response.redirect(...)` (or `NextResponse.redirect`) and add `state` validation to prevent CSRF.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:11Z on app/api/teams/[id]/members/route.ts:21 ---
This members listing endpoint does not verify the requester belongs to the team; it will expose member emails/names to any authenticated user who guesses a team ID. Check membership/authorization (e.g., require `getUserTeamRole` non-null) before calling `getTeamMembers`.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:12Z on core/api/response.ts:27 ---
`successResponse` is hard-coded to return HTTP 200 and only accepts `(data, meta)`, but multiple route handlers in this PR call it with a third `status` argument (e.g. `..., undefined, 201`), which will fail type-checking. Consider extending `successResponse` to accept an optional `status` parameter (default 200) and pass it through to `Response.json` so call sites can return 201/other codes consistently.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:12Z on app/api/notifications/stream/route.ts:46 ---
The stream cleanup logic is broken: `stream` is referenced inside its own `ReadableStream` `start()` callback, and calling `stream.cancel()` from within `start()` is not how disconnect cleanup is triggered. This can throw at runtime and/or leak intervals/subscriptions. Implement an underlying source `cancel()` handler (or listen to `request.signal.abort`) to call `unsubscribe()`/`clearInterval()` when the client disconnects.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-02-27T12:34:10Z on app/api/teams/[id]/route.ts:13 ---
This endpoint returns team details for any authenticated user who knows a team ID. Since `getTeam()` is not access-controlled, the route should verify the requester is a member (e.g., via `getUserTeamRole`) before returning the team, otherwise it leaks org metadata.
